"""
MKT Original Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1samuel-1-3-full.py

84 missing verses: ch1 (28), ch2 (35 — v2:2 already exists), ch3 (21)
Layer: mkt-original — lexical/semantic Hebrew commentary

Key lexical themes:
- šāʾal / Samuel name etymology (asked/lent to YHWH); šāḵan in ch1 wordplay
- YHWH Ṣəḇāʾôt: first sustained use of 'LORD of Hosts' title in Samuel
- Hannah's prayer: qeren (horn), māšîaḥ (anointed), šeʾôl, ḥāsîd, kāḇēḏ
- bənê bĕliyyaʿal vs. Samuel's faithful ministry; contrasting uses of yāḏaʿ
- Samuel's call: dāḇar YHWH, yāqār (rare), ḥāzôn (vision), nāḇîʾ, nāpal ʾārṣāh
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ORIGINAL = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The story opens with <em>ʾîš ʾeḥāḏ</em> ('a certain man') — the same formula as Judg 13:2 (Manoah's introduction) and Ruth 1:1 (Elimelech's introduction). The formula marks an ordinary Israelite whose family will become the vehicle for YHWH's extraordinary purpose. <em>Rāmātayim</em> (H7436, dual of <em>rāmāh</em>, heights) — two heights; <em>ṣôpîm</em> (watchers/Zuphites). Elkanah (<em>ʾelqānāh</em> H511) means 'God has created/acquired' — a theophoric name with <em>ʾēl</em> and <em>qānāh</em> (the root of Gen 14:19: 'God Most High, creator of heaven and earth'). His four-generation genealogy roots him in the clan of Zuph of Ephraim (the land of Zuph reappears in 1 Sam 9:5).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The two-wife structure: <em>Ḥannāh</em> (H2584, grace/favor — from <em>ḥēn</em>) and <em>Pĕninnāh</em> (H6444, possibly from <em>pənînîm</em>, corals/rubies — Prov 3:15; 8:11 use the word for what wisdom exceeds in value). <em>ʿāqārāh</em> (H6135, barren) — the theologically loaded term for a woman YHWH has not opened. The OT's barren-matriarch pattern: Sarah (Gen 11:30) → Rebekah (Gen 25:21) → Rachel (Gen 29:31) → Samson's mother (Judg 13:2) → Hannah. Each barrenness is YHWH's withholding before miraculous provision of a child with a covenantal role. The pattern marks Samuel as one in that line before his birth is narrated.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>YHWH Ṣəḇāʾôt</em> (LORD of Armies/Hosts) — this divine title appears with new frequency in Samuel; <em>ṣāḇāʾ</em> (H6635, army/host) denotes earthly armies, the heavenly angelic forces, and the stars (the host of heaven). The title asserts YHWH's military-cosmic sovereignty. Shiloh (<em>šilôh</em> H7887) was the central sanctuary during the judges period, housing the ark (Josh 18:1). Eli's sons Hophni and Phinehas are introduced in the same verse as the annual sacrifice — a narrative anticipation that these two are inseparable from the worship context that will expose their corruption.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The annual sacrifice generates <em>mānōt</em> (portions, H4490, from <em>mānāh</em> H4487, to count/apportion) distributed to family members. The portions represent the offerer's share in the peace offering (<em>šĕlāmîm</em>) eaten as communion with YHWH. Deut 12:11-12 mandates that the whole household — including servants — share in this meal. Elkanah's distribution sets up v5's tension: giving portions to Peninnah and her children (the fruitful wife) while reserving a special portion for Hannah (the barren one who is nevertheless loved) frames the conflict between social fruitfulness and covenantal love.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Elkanah gives Hannah <em>mānāh ʾaḥat ʾappāyim</em> — a double or choice portion; the exact phrase is unique and debated: 'double portion' (double of what the others received), or 'a portion of two faces/nostrils' (a sighing portion, i.e., accompanied by grief). The theological note — 'because YHWH had closed her womb' (<em>kî-ʾāḥar rāḥam YHWH bĕʿaḏāh</em>) — directly attributes Hannah's barrenness to divine action. This is consistent throughout the OT: YHWH 'closes' (Gen 20:18) and 'opens' (Gen 29:31; 30:22) wombs as sovereign acts. The attribution prevents a purely biological reading and frames Hannah's condition as a theological state awaiting divine resolution.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Peninnah is called Hannah's <em>ṣārāh</em> (H6869, rival/adversary — the technical term for a co-wife in a polygamous household; Lev 18:18 uses the root to regulate taking 'a woman as a rival to her sister'). Her <em>kaʿas</em> (H3707, provocation/vexing) is directed at Hannah 'because YHWH had closed her womb.' Peninnah weaponizes the evidence of divine action — Hannah's barrenness as visible sign of YHWH's withholding — as the basis for social mockery. YHWH's closing of the womb is thus made the catalyst for the prayer that will become the occasion of YHWH's opening it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The pattern repeats annually (<em>šānāh ḇĕšānāh</em>): Hannah weeps and does not eat. Two standard markers of deep mourning in Hebrew culture (cf. David for Bathsheba's first son, 2 Sam 12:16; Ahab's sulking, 1 Kgs 21:4). The sanctuary visit — which Deut 16:11-14 commands as a time of rejoicing — becomes Hannah's annual moment of deepest grief. The gap between what YHWH commands (rejoice at the feast) and what YHWH has given her cause for (grief over barrenness) is the story's emotional architecture. The liturgical feast as the occasion of deepest personal anguish sets up prayer that is prayer indeed — not ritual performance but desperate petition.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elkanah's consolation — 'Am I not better to you than ten sons?' — uses the number ten as the superlative-complete number (the ideal family size implying more than enough). His misreading: he interprets Hannah's grief as a relational deficit when it is a theological and social condition (barrenness is a divine closure, a social shame, a missing covenant blessing). What a husband's affection cannot supply — the covenant blessing of children — YHWH alone can give. Elkanah's genuine love and genuine misunderstanding together make Hannah's turn to YHWH in prayer the only remaining recourse.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Hannah rises (<em>wayyāqom</em>) after eating at Shiloh — textually debated; LXX suggests she rose before eating. <em>mārah lāh</em> (it was bitter to her) uses the root <em>mārar</em> (H4843, to be bitter) — the same root as Naomi's Mara (Ruth 1:20). The bitterness of soul (<em>marāh nāpeš</em>) is a recognized OT psychological-spiritual state (Job 3:20; 7:11). Eli is positioned at the doorpost of the sanctuary (<em>mĕzûzat hêḵal YHWH</em>): the threshold-guardian whose role is to mediate between worshipers and YHWH, but who will in this scene misread the most authentic prayer before him.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>Waṯṯitpallēl ʿal-YHWH</em> — she prayed to YHWH. <em>pālal</em> (H6419, to pray/intercede) in the reflexive Hithpael means to interpose oneself before God — the prayer-form that brings oneself before the divine presence. <em>wāḇāḵōh ṯiḇkeh</em> (weeping she wept) — the cognate infinitive absolute intensifies: her weeping was complete, sustained, total. The combination of prayer and intense weeping characterizes the OT's most urgent intercession (Ezra 10:1; Ps 6:6; Hezekiah in Isa 38:2-3). Hannah's prayer is the OT model for petition that combines explicit request, vow, and complete emotional disclosure before YHWH.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hannah's vow (<em>neder</em> H5088) contains: (1) invocation of YHWH Ṣəḇāʾôt; (2) double infinitive absolute 'if you will indeed see' (<em>rāʾōh tirʾeh</em>) — emphatic appeal; (3) the covenant verb <em>zāḵar</em> (remember me — active covenant engagement, not mere recall: Gen 8:1 [Noah], Gen 30:22 [Rachel]); (4) 'not forget your servant'; (5) specific petition: 'give your servant a male child'; (6) reciprocal vow: 'I will give him to YHWH all the days of his life'; (7) Nazirite sign: 'a razor shall not come upon his head.' The Nazirite vow (Num 6:1-21) combined no wine, no razor, no corpse contact — Hannah specifies the razor. The Qumran Samuel text expands the conditions; the LXX adds wine.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The verb <em>hirḇĕṯāh lĕhitpallēl</em> (she multiplied/continued her prayer) — Eli watches (<em>šōmēr</em>, H8104) from his seat at the doorpost. Eli's position — <em>ʿal-hakkissēʾ ʿal-mĕzûzat hêḵal YHWH</em> (on the seat by the doorpost of the temple of YHWH) — places him at the threshold between outer and inner sanctuary, the liturgical guardian. The <em>hêḵal</em> (H1964) is the main hall of the Shiloh sanctuary, the term used for both the tabernacle's inner structure and later the Solomonic temple. Eli sees lip movement without sound — and misreads it.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Hannah's prayer is <em>mĕḏabberet ʿal-libbāh</em> (speaking upon her heart) — silent, lip-only prayer without audible voice. This is one of the OT's earliest descriptions of purely mental prayer (as opposed to spoken petition). <em>Qôlāh lōʾ yiššāmēaʿ</em> (her voice was not heard) — the silent petition addressed to YHWH alone, not audible to human witnesses, is a theological statement about the audience of prayer. Eli's misreading of silent devotion as public drunkenness is doubly ironic: the priest who fails to discipline his sons' public sacrilege condemns the woman whose private prayer is exemplary.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Eli's accusation — <em>ʿaḏ-māṯay tiššəkārîn</em> (how long will you be drunk?) — uses <em>šāḵar</em> (H7937, to be drunk). The irony: Eli's sons are guilty of cultic violations in the same sanctuary (2:13-17), yet the priest accuses the praying woman of drunkenness. His instruction — 'put away your wine' (<em>hāsîrî ʾet-yênēḵ</em>) — reads the external sign (moving lips, no sound) without perceiving the internal reality. This failure of spiritual discernment characterizes Eli throughout: he observes external forms while missing inner realities — the same failure that will make him unable to see YHWH's presence while Samuel receives it in the same room (ch3).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Hannah's self-defense: '<em>ʾiššāh qĕšat-rûaḥ ʾānōḵî</em>' — I am a hard/pressed-spirit woman. <em>qāšāh</em> (H7186, hard/severe) applied to <em>rûaḥ</em>: her spirit is under severe pressure. 'I have poured out my soul before YHWH' — <em>šāpaḵ ʾet-napšî lipnê YHWH</em>: the metaphor of pouring out (<em>šāpaḵ</em>, H8210, to pour/spill out) the <em>nepeš</em> (soul/inner self/animating life) before YHWH captures the image of total self-disclosure in prayer. Used in Ps 42:4 ('I pour out my soul') and Lam 2:19 ('Pour out your heart like water before the face of the Lord'). The image treats the person as a vessel whose entire inner contents are emptied before YHWH in prayer.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Do not regard your servant as a daughter of Belial' — <em>al-tittēn ʾet-ʾamaṯḵā lipnê bat-bĕliyyāʿal</em>. <em>bat-bĕliyyāʿal</em> (daughter of worthlessness/Belial) — the feminine form of the descriptor the narrator will apply to Eli's sons in 2:12 (<em>bĕnê bĕliyyāʿal</em>). The irony is sharp: Eli is applying to the praying woman the exact characterization that correctly describes his own sons. <em>Bĕliyyāʿal</em> (H1100): 'without profit/worth' or 'without ascending' — a compound of <em>bĕlî</em> (without) + <em>yaʿal</em> (profit/value). She concludes: 'I have been speaking from the abundance of my complaint and grief' (<em>mērōḇ śîḥî wĕḵaʿăśî</em>) — <em>śîaḥ</em> (H7879, anxious musing/complaint) + <em>kaʿas</em> (H3707, vexation/grief) — the vocabulary of deep grief-prayer.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Eli's blessing — <em>lĕḵî lĕšālôm</em> (go in peace) — is the standard priestly benediction. 'The God of Israel grant your petition which you have asked of him' (<em>wĕʾĕlōhê yiśrāʾēl yittēn ʾet-šĕlātēḵ ʾăšer šāʾalt</em>) — the verb <em>šāʾal</em> (H7592, to ask/request) appears here for the first time in the chapter and will dominate vv18-28. The blessing is pronounced without Eli knowing the content of the petition — he is endorsing the form (earnest prayer) before knowing the substance. This is the priestly blessing functioning as a genuine covenant channel: the blessing pronounced in YHWH's name has efficacy regardless of the priest's knowledge of its specific application.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hannah goes away, eats, and 'her face was no longer sad' (<em>ûpānehā lōʾ-hāyû-lāh ʿôḏ</em>) — before any empirical change in her condition. The change in countenance signals an inner resolution: she has transferred her burden to YHWH in prayer, and the priestly blessing has confirmed YHWH's receipt of it. This is the OT portrait of the faith that receives before the evidence — the peace that precedes the answer (cf. Phil 4:6-7: 'in everything by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving let your requests be made known to God, and the peace of God will guard your hearts'). The mechanism is the same: full petition → transferred burden → peace.</p>",
    "19": "<p>They rise early (<em>wayyaškimû babboqer</em>) and worship before YHWH — the morning worship follows the prayer-and-blessing sequence. 'And YHWH remembered her' (<em>wayyizkor-āh YHWH</em>) — <em>zāḵar</em> (H2142, to remember) is the covenant verb of divine initiative: YHWH 'remembered' Noah (Gen 8:1), Abraham (Gen 19:29), Rachel (Gen 30:22). YHWH's remembering is not the recovery of forgotten information but the active covenant engagement that initiates fulfillment. The verse's pairing of 'Elkanah knew Hannah his wife' with 'YHWH remembered her' places human and divine action in sequence: the means (normal marital relations) and the agency (YHWH's active covenant remembering) are both present.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Hannah conceives and bears a son named <em>Šĕmûʾēl</em> (Samuel H8050). The etymology given — 'because I asked him from YHWH' (<em>kî mēYHWH šĕʾiltîw</em>) — is based on <em>šāʾal</em> (to ask). The name's literal elements are more likely <em>šēm</em> (name) + <em>ʾēl</em> (God) = 'his name is God' or 'heard of God' — but the <em>šāʾal</em> etymology fits better the name <em>Šāʾûl</em> (Saul). This is a much-discussed lexical tension: the etymology that belongs to Saul's name is given to Samuel. Some scholars read this as deliberate — the man who embodies YHWH's 'asking' (the one truly given to YHWH) is Samuel, while the king Israel will 'ask for' (<em>šāʾal</em>) in ch8 is Saul. The <em>šāʾal</em> wordplay will saturate the chapter's conclusion.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Elkanah goes up to make the yearly sacrifice and pay his vow (<em>ʾet-nidĕrô</em>) — a vow not narrated previously, suggesting he also made a commitment at the Shiloh visit. Hannah decides not to go until Samuel is weaned — standard Iron Age practice was nursing for 2-3 years. The specific mention of Elkanah's vow suggests both spouses responded to Hannah's crisis with vows; the narrative focuses on Hannah's because it is the one that directly concerned Samuel's dedication. The transition sets up the tension: Hannah will fulfill her vow when the child is old enough to remain permanently at the sanctuary.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Hannah's stated intention — 'he may appear before YHWH and remain there forever' (<em>wĕyāšaḇ šām ʿad-ʿôlām</em>) — uses <em>ʿôlām</em> (H5769, forever/indefinitely). The same word governs YHWH's covenant promises (Abrahamic, Davidic). Hannah applies the covenant-permanence vocabulary to her son's service: not a temporary loan but a permanent dedication. Elkanah's response — 'only may YHWH establish his word' (<em>yāqēm YHWH ʾet-dĕḇārô</em>) — implies that YHWH has already spoken a word concerning Samuel (through the priestly blessing, or a direct oracle not narrated), and the proper response to fulfilling the vow is to invoke YHWH's confirmation of his own prior word.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Elkanah's phrase 'only may YHWH establish his word' — the LXX reads 'establish what proceeds from your mouth' (harmonizing to Hannah's vow), but MT's 'his word' (<em>dĕḇārô</em>) refers to a prior YHWH word about Samuel. If the priestly blessing of v17 is in view, Elkanah is invoking its fulfillment; alternatively, a direct divine communication not narrated here may be implied. Either way, Elkanah frames Hannah's vow-fulfillment within YHWH's own prior speech — the human vow-keeping and divine word-keeping are aligned as a single purpose-event.</p>",
    "24": "<p>When Samuel is weaned, Hannah brings him to Shiloh with a three-year-old bull (<em>par mĕšulaš</em>), an ephah of flour (<em>ʾêpāh ʾaḥat qemeaḥ</em>), and a skin of wine (<em>nēḇel yāyin</em>). The three-year-old bull is the peak-maturity sacrificial animal — Numbers 15:8-10 prescribes a bull for major vow-fulfillment offerings. The full sacrificial equipment (bull, flour, wine — the components of a grain offering with liquid accompaniment) signals that this is a vow-fulfillment offering of the highest grade. <em>Wĕhannaʿar nāʿar</em> (the boy was young) — the repetition of the <em>naʿar</em> root emphasizes his youth, setting up the contrast between his smallness and the gravity of the covenant act about to occur.</p>",
    "25": "<p>They slaughter the bull and bring the child to Eli — the sacrifice precedes the presentation. The sequence (sacrifice → bring to Eli → present to YHWH) follows the vow-fulfillment pattern: the sacrifice ratifies the vow; the priest receives the dedication; the child enters permanent sanctuary service. Samuel is being given not as Eli's personal servant but as YHWH's sanctuary servant — the distinction will become critical in ch2 when Samuel's faithful ministry contrasts with Eli's sons' corruption. The scene's formality emphasizes the covenant seriousness of the transfer: this is legally binding dedication, not a temporary lending.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Hannah's self-identification to Eli — 'I am the woman who was standing here in your presence, praying to YHWH' — uses the oath formula <em>bî ʾăḏōnî ḥay napšĕḵā</em> ('as your soul lives, my lord'). The anamnesis: 'I am the woman' (<em>ʾānî hāʾiššāh</em>) — the woman Eli could not correctly identify when he saw her praying now identifies herself in the light of what YHWH has done. The priest who called her drunk is looking at the answered prayer. The identification without reproach or triumph is itself a form of <em>hesed</em>: she returns in gratitude, not in score-settling.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'For this child I prayed, and YHWH has granted me my petition which I asked of him' — <em>wayyittēn YHWH lî ʾet-šĕʾēlātî ʾăšer šāʾaltî mēʿimmô</em>. The verse concentrates the <em>šāʾal</em> vocabulary: <em>šĕʾēlātî</em> (my petition, what-I-asked) and <em>šāʾaltî</em> (I asked). The fulfillment of prayer is expressed as exact correspondence between petition and answer: she asked for <em>this child</em>, YHWH gave precisely what was asked. The verb <em>nātan</em> (gave) — YHWH as the giver who matches his gift to the specific request — is the theology of answered prayer (James 1:5: 'God gives generously to all without finding fault').</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Therefore I have lent him to YHWH. As long as he lives, he is lent to YHWH' — <em>wĕgam ʾānōḵî hišʾiltîhû laYHWH ... šāʾûl laYHWH</em>. The final wordplay: <em>hišʾiltîhû</em> (I have asked/lent him out — the Hiphil of <em>šāʾal</em>) and <em>šāʾûl laYHWH</em> (he is asked-for/lent to YHWH — the passive participle). <em>šāʾûl</em> is precisely the name of Saul (the future king Israel will 'ask for' in ch8). Samuel ends ch1 described as <em>šāʾûl laYHWH</em> — the lexical shadow of the coming king falls over the closing of the story of the prophet who will anoint him. The chapter that is about Samuel's naming ends with the word that names Saul.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>Hannah's prayer opens: <em>ʿālaz libbî bYHWH rāmāh qarnî bYHWH</em> — my heart exults in YHWH; my horn is exalted in YHWH. <em>ʿālaz</em> (H5937, exult intensely — used in Ps 28:7; Zeph 3:14) connotes fierce, fighting joy. <em>qeren</em> (H7161, horn) — the horn of a bull or ram as the seat of its power; 'my horn is exalted' means my strength/dignity/honor has been lifted. Hannah's prayer closes (v10) with <em>wĕyārēm qeren mĕšîḥô</em> (he will exalt the horn of his anointed) — the same <em>rûm qeren</em> formula. The opening personal exaltation and the closing messianic exaltation are connected: Hannah's lifted horn is the prototype of the ultimate horn-exaltation. Mary's Magnificat (Luke 1:46-55) expands this prayer, applying the reversals to the coming of the Messiah.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Do not speak with such great pride' — <em>ʾal-tarḇû tĕḏabbĕrû gĕḇōhāh gĕḇōhāh</em>: the doubled <em>gĕḇōhāh</em> (H1364, high/proud) is an intensifying repetition. 'YHWH is a God of knowledges' (<em>ʾēl dēʿôt YHWH</em>) — the plural <em>dēʿôt</em> (knowledges) indicates exhaustive or multidimensional knowledge. 'And by him actions are weighed' (<em>wĕlô niṯkĕnû ʿălilôt</em>) — <em>tāḵan</em> (H8254, to weigh/assess) is used in Prov 16:2; 21:2 for YHWH's weighing of human spirits. The sovereignty of YHWH's knowledge grounds the prohibition of arrogance: one cannot boast before the One who weighs every action in his comprehensive, plural knowledge.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'The bows of the mighty are shattered, but those who stumbled are girded with strength' — <em>qešet gibbōrîm ḥattîm wĕniḵšālîm ʾāzĕrû ḥāyil</em>. <em>gibbōrîm</em> (H1368, mighty warriors) are those who rely on their military strength; their bows (<em>qešet</em>, the premier long-range weapon) are 'shattered' (<em>ḥattat</em>, H2865 — the same root as 'terror/dismay' that overcomes enemies). <em>niḵšālîm</em> (those who stumbled, H3782) — the visibly vulnerable who are then 'girded with strength' (<em>ʾāzar ḥayil</em>). The pattern — strong rendered powerless, stumbling made strong — is the theological reversal Paul applies in 1 Cor 1:27-29 and that the cross itself enacts.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The barren woman has borne seven, but she who has many children languishes' (<em>ʿăqārāh yāleḏāh šiḇʿāh wĕraḇbat bānîm ʾumlālāh</em>). The seven children (the perfect, complete number — seven as fullness) born to the formerly barren is the direct application to Hannah: she was barren; YHWH will give her five more children (v21) approaching the prayer's 'seven.' The 'many-son woman' (<em>raḇbat bānîm</em>) — Peninnah — who now 'languishes' (<em>ʾumlālāh</em>, H535, wilts/weakens). The prayer is simultaneously a theological statement about YHWH's reversals and a personal testimony about Hannah's own experience — and a prophecy about what is coming for Peninnah's position of advantage.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'YHWH kills and makes alive; he brings down to Sheol and raises up' (<em>YHWH mēmît ûmĕḥayyeh môrîḏ šĕʾôl wayaʿal</em>). This is the OT's most direct paired statement of divine sovereignty over life and death before Deut 32:39. <em>šĕʾôl</em> (H7585) — the realm of the dead, conceived as below the earth (Job 10:21-22; Ps 88:3-6). YHWH's power to 'bring up' from Sheol (<em>wayyaʿal</em>, to ascend/bring up) is the background for NT resurrection language. Deut 32:39 parallels exactly: 'I kill and make alive.' Both texts assert the same monotheistic sovereignty: YHWH alone controls the boundary between life and death — no competing power shares this authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'He raises up the poor from the dust, lifts the needy from the ash heap' (<em>mĕqîm mēʿāfār dāl mēʾašpōt yārîm ʾeḇyôn</em>). <em>ʿāfār</em> (H6083, dust/earth) — the lowest position, associated with mourning (Job 2:12) and humiliation (Isa 47:1). <em>ʾašpōt</em> (H830, ash-heap/dung-heap/refuse pile) — where the destitute and sick sat (Job 2:8). Ps 113:7-8 quotes these phrases almost verbatim: 'He raises the poor from the dust and lifts the needy from the ash heap, to make them sit with princes.' The ash-heap as the lowest social location from which YHWH lifts his faithful ones is the OT's canonical image of divine reversal — social and economic inversion as YHWH's self-expression.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'For the pillars of the earth are YHWH's, and on them he has set the world' (<em>kî lYHWH mĕṣûqê ʾereṣ wayyāšeṯ ʿălêhem tēḇēl</em>). <em>mĕṣûqê ʾereṣ</em> (H4690, pillars/pegs of the earth) — the cosmological foundations that support the world. The cosmic grounding of the social reversal is the prayer's key insight: YHWH can reverse human fortunes because he owns and controls the foundations of creation. The one who set the world on its pillars can lift a person from the ash heap to the prince's seat — both acts are expressions of the same sovereign power operating at different scales of reality.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'He will guard the feet of his faithful ones, but the wicked shall be cut off in darkness' (<em>raglê ḥăsîḏāyw yišmōr wĕrĕšāʿîm baḥōšeḵ yiddāmmû</em>). <em>ḥăsîḏāyw</em> (H2623, his faithful/covenant-loyal ones) — plural of <em>ḥāsîḏ</em>, one who practices <em>hesed</em>. 'For not by strength shall a man prevail' (<em>kî lōʾ ḇĕkoaḥ yiḡbar ʾîš</em>). This summary principle dissolves the apparent security of the strong: human strength is never the decisive factor in YHWH's economy. The strong fall not because of a rival's greater strength but because YHWH does not honor self-reliance. This theological axiom grounds every reversal in the prayer: the source of outcomes is YHWH's initiative, not human capacity.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'He will give strength to his king and exalt the horn of his anointed' (<em>wĕyārēm qeren mĕšîḥô</em>). The climax of Hannah's prayer is the first use of <em>māšîaḥ</em> (H4899, his anointed one) in Samuel. At this point in the narrative there is no king in Israel — Hannah prays for a future king and anointed one in the same breath as describing YHWH's reversals. The prayer thus looks beyond Samuel (YHWH's immediate answer to Hannah's prayer) to the king YHWH will establish (the structural answer to Israel's need) — and beyond Israel's historical kings to the ultimate <em>māšîaḥ</em>. Acts 2:36 ('God has made him both Lord and Christ') and Rev 12:10 ('the kingdom of our God and the authority of his Christ') are the full realization of this first <em>māšîaḥ</em> invocation.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Elkanah returns to Ramah; Samuel ministers before YHWH under Eli. <em>mĕšārēt</em> (H8334, to minister/serve in sanctuary context) — the technical term for Levitical and priestly ministry (Num 8:22; Deut 10:8). Samuel, an Ephraimite rather than a Levite, ministers at the central sanctuary — his role transcends ordinary tribal categories, anticipating the prophetic office that will also transcend tribal boundaries. The contrast is established: Samuel <em>ministers before YHWH</em>; Eli's sons (about to be introduced) minister for themselves.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Eli's sons are <em>bĕnê bĕliyyāʿal</em> (sons of worthlessness/Belial) who 'did not know YHWH' (<em>lōʾ yāḏĕʿû ʾet-YHWH</em>). <em>yāḏaʿ</em> (H3045, to know) in the covenantal sense means relational, personal knowledge — the knowledge that comes from covenant relationship. The same verb will describe Samuel's condition in 3:7 ('Samuel did not yet know YHWH') — but the situations are opposite: Eli's sons do not know YHWH due to spiritual corruption; Samuel does not yet know YHWH because YHWH has not yet revealed himself to him. Same surface description, opposite diagnoses. The sons' not-knowing is culpable; Samuel's not-knowing is circumstantial.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The priests' sin is technically precise: a three-pronged fork (<em>mazlēg</em> H4207) used to take from the boiling sacrificial pot before the fat was burned to YHWH. Lev 3:3-5 and 7:29-34 specify that the fat must be burned to YHWH first and the breast and right thigh given to the priest. Hophni and Phinehas are taking before YHWH's portion — inverting the sacrificial order and claiming priority over YHWH. This is the specific violation: not taking an unauthorized amount but taking at the wrong time, before the sacred portion designated for YHWH. The timing violation is the theological content of the sin.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The three-pronged fork's arbitrary catch — 'all that the fork brought up, the priest took' — reflects the opportunistic character of the sin. No prescribed portion is being observed; the priests take whatever they can get. The verb <em>kōhēn</em> (acting as priest) used in v13 is deeply ironic: those who exercise the priestly office are doing so for self-service. The corruption of sacred office — using covenant functions as vehicles for personal enrichment — is the OT's consistent warning about the danger that attaches to positions of sacred privilege (cf. Ezek 34 on self-serving shepherds).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The sin escalates: even before the fat was burned (<em>bĕṭerem yaqṭirûn ʾet-haḥēleḇ</em>), the priest's servant demands raw meat rather than boiled. The preference for raw over cooked meat is a quality preference — roasted meat is superior to boiled. The progression: improper timing (before YHWH's portion is burned) → improper method (raw for roasting rather than the prescribed cooked portion). The escalation pattern is the OT's description of how sin in religious office compounds: first a small violation of timing, then an escalation to a quality preference, then (v16) outright coercion. Sin in sacred office follows an escalating logic.</p>",
    "16": "<p>If the worshiper protests — 'burn the fat first, then take as much as you wish' — the servant's response is coercive: 'No, you must give it now; if not, I will take it by force' (<em>wĕʾim-lōʾ lāqaḥtî ḇĕḥāzāqāh</em>). <em>ḥāzāq</em> (H2388, force/strength) applied to the taking of sacrificial portions is the language of extortion. The priest who should facilitate the worshiper's offering to YHWH is now threatening force against the worshiper. This is the inversion of the priestly role from covenant mediator to covenant predator — using the authority of the priestly office as a coercive instrument against the very people the priest exists to serve.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'The sin of the young men was very great in the sight of YHWH, for the men treated the offering of YHWH with contempt' (<em>kî nîʾăṣû hāʾănāšîm ʾet-minḥat YHWH</em>). <em>nāʾaṣ</em> (H5006, to despise/contemn) — used in Num 14:23 for those who treated YHWH with contempt in the wilderness. The 'offering of YHWH' (<em>minḥat YHWH</em>) is the vehicle of the contempt: by taking before YHWH's portion and by using coercion, the priests make the worship system express contempt toward YHWH rather than honor. The narrator's theological precision: the gravity of the sin is not violation of a procedure but the contempt it expresses toward YHWH himself. Contempt for the sacred is contempt for the Holy One.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel ministers before YHWH as a <em>naʿar</em> (youth) wearing a linen ephod (<em>ʾēpôḏ bāḏ</em>). The <em>ʾēpôḏ</em> (H646) was primarily the high-priestly garment (Exod 28:6-14) associated with the Urim and Thummim oracle-function (Exod 28:30). Samuel wearing the ephod at this young age — though he is not a Levite — foreshadows his prophetic-oracular role. The contrast with Eli's sons is stark: they take meat for themselves; Samuel wears the vestment of priestly ministry. The linen ephod as the badge of genuine covenant service (cf. 2 Sam 6:14 where David wears it) marks Samuel as the growing alternative to the corrupt priestly establishment.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hannah makes a little robe (<em>mĕʿîl qāṭōn</em>) for Samuel each year. <em>mĕʿîl</em> (H4598, robe/outer garment) — the same word for Samuel's prophetic robe in his adult ministry (15:27; 28:14). The annual garment is Hannah's ongoing investment in Samuel despite his absence: the mother who gave her son to YHWH remains connected to him through the yearly robe. The robe tracks his growth — each year a new robe, each year larger. Hannah's faithfulness to Samuel mirrors YHWH's faithfulness to Hannah: both continue their covenant relationship across distance.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Eli's blessing on Elkanah and Hannah — 'May YHWH give you children by this woman in place of the one she asked for YHWH' (<em>taḥat haššĕʾēlāh ʾăšer šāʾal lYHWH</em>) — uses <em>šāʾal</em> again: 'in place of the requesting she asked.' The blessing-language of substitution (<em>taḥat</em>, in place of/instead of) is significant: Hannah's gift to YHWH will be replaced by YHWH's gift to Hannah. The exchange is not equal — Samuel was given once; YHWH will give five more. This is the economics of Prov 11:24-25: 'One gives freely yet grows all the richer.' YHWH's reciprocal giving exceeds the human giving that initiated it.</p>",
    "21": "<p>YHWH visits (<em>pāqaḏ</em>, H6485 — the covenant verb of divine initiative, as in 1:19) Hannah and she conceives three more sons and two daughters. The five additional children approaching the seven of Hannah's prayer (v5) represent YHWH's abundant answer. Samuel 'grew' (<em>wayyiḡdal šĕmûʾēl</em>) with YHWH (<em>ʿim YHWH</em>) — the presence of YHWH characterizes his formation. The brief notice of Samuel's growth between the narratives of Eli's corrupt sons and the oracle against Eli's house (vv22-36) keeps the alternative before the reader: while Eli's house disintegrates, YHWH's chosen servant grows.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Eli confronts his sons: 'they lay with the women who were serving at the entrance to the tent of meeting' (<em>ʾet-hannāšîm haṣṣōḇĕʾôt petaḥ ʾōhel môʿēḏ</em>). These women were mentioned in Exod 38:8 as performing some function at the tabernacle entrance. The violation of sanctuary servants by the priests is a desecration of both sanctuary and persons. The two violations together — theft from the altar (vv13-17) and sexual exploitation of sanctuary staff (v22) — constitute total inversion of the priestly calling: the priest who should guard the sacred space and protect the vulnerable has become both thief and predator.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Eli hears reports (<em>šōmēaʿ ʾet-dĕḇārêhem</em>) from all the people and verbally rebukes his sons — but does not remove them from office. This gap between hearing/knowing and acting to remove is the narrator's critique of Eli's leadership. The information is available; the authority is present; the will is absent. 3:13 will render the explicit verdict: 'his sons were blaspheming God, and he did not restrain them (<em>wĕlōʾ kihāh bām</em>).' The verb <em>kāhāh</em> (H3543, to restrain/rebuke/grow dim) connects Eli's failure to restrain his sons to his own 'growing dim' — the same root for both his ethical and physical weakness.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'It is no good report that I hear the people of YHWH spreading about' — <em>maʿăḇîrîm ʿam-YHWH</em> (the people of YHWH spreading it). The <em>šĕmûʿāh</em> (H8052, report/fame) of YHWH's sanctuary in the community is at stake. The priests who should cause YHWH's name to be honored among his people are causing evil reports to spread instead. Ezek 36:20-23 diagnoses Israel's exile as the consequence of this same dynamic: profaning YHWH's name among the peoples. The priestly function of maintaining YHWH's honor in the community's speech is the inverse of what Hophni and Phinehas are producing.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'If someone sins against a man, God can mediate (<em>wĕpillel lô ʾĕlōhîm</em>); but if someone sins against YHWH, who can intercede?' (<em>mî yitpallel-lô</em>). The root <em>pālal</em> (H6419) appears in both verbs: God mediates/arbitrates (<em>piel</em>: to serve as mediator) human-human conflicts; but for sin against YHWH there is no higher court of appeal. The distinction is crucial: the sins of Hophni and Phinehas are not merely against worshipers but against YHWH himself — they have stolen his portions and desecrated his house. 'But they would not listen to their father's voice, because YHWH desired to kill them' (<em>kî ḥāpēṣ YHWH lahămîtām</em>) — the divine will in their judicial hardening: YHWH's decision to judge them is the reason the rebuke cannot reach them.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Now the young man Samuel continued to grow both in stature and in favor with YHWH and with men' (<em>wĕhannāʿar šĕmûʾēl hōlēḵ wĕḡāḏōl wāṭôḇ gam ʿim-YHWH wĕgam ʿim-ʾănāšîm</em>). The formula of double-favor (with YHWH and with men) appears in Luke 2:52 for Jesus: 'And Jesus increased in wisdom and in stature and in favor with God and man.' Both Samuel and Jesus are described with this double-alignment formula. The OT use establishes the pattern: the covenant servant who grows in YHWH's estimation and in human recognition is the model for the one who will perfectly embody this double-favor in the messianic age.</p>",
    "27": "<p>An unnamed 'man of God' (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) delivers an oracle against Eli's house. The designation 'man of God' is used for prophets throughout the historical books (Moses in Deut 33:1; the unnamed prophet in Judg 13:6; Elijah in 1 Kgs 17:18; Elisha throughout 2 Kgs). The oracle begins with YHWH's prior revelation to the Aaronic priesthood in Egypt — '<em>niglōh niglêṯî</em>' (I revealed — did I indeed reveal?) — the doubly emphatic infinitive absolute stressing the certainty and completeness of the original revelation. The oracle frames the judgment as covenant violation: YHWH gave extraordinary privilege; extraordinary privilege has been extraordinarily corrupted.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The threefold catalog of YHWH's gifts to Aaron's house: (1) chosen from all tribes; (2) altar access; (3) incense-burning. Plus: wearing the ephod; eating the fire offerings. Each item represents a layer of covenant privilege — access to the divine presence, mediation, oracular equipment, and sacrificial sustenance. The catalog's comprehensiveness makes the corruption more indictable: every dimension of covenant privilege has been turned into a vehicle for self-enrichment. The inventory of gift before the verdict of abuse is the OT's standard covenant-lawsuit pattern: 'I gave you everything; you turned everything into something for yourselves.'</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Why do you scorn my sacrifices... and honor your sons above me?' (<em>wattĕkabbēḏ ʾet-bānêḵā mimmennî</em>). The verb <em>kāḇēḏ</em> (H3513, to honor/glorify — the root of <em>kāḇôḏ</em>, glory) used here and in v30: Eli has honored (<em>kāḇēḏ</em>) his sons more than he honored YHWH (<em>mimmennî</em>). The sin is one of disordered honor: giving to his sons the weight of priority that belongs to YHWH. This is the specific violation of the first commandment at the household level — functionally placing his sons before YHWH in the order of his decisive actions. The sin of inaction is the same as actively choosing his sons over YHWH.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'Those who honor me I will honor; those who despise me shall be lightly esteemed' (<em>kî mĕkabbĕḏay ʾăkabbēḏ ûḇōzay yēqāllû</em>). This is the covenant honor-economy's most explicit statement: the <em>kāḇēḏ</em> (honor/weight) you give to YHWH is the measure of what you receive in return. <em>bāzāh</em> (H959, to despise/treat as contemptible) → <em>qālal</em> (H7043, to make light/contemptible). The reversal applies: Eli's sons who 'despised' (<em>nāʾaṣ</em>, v17) YHWH's offerings will themselves be made contemptible. The law of sowing and reaping applied to the honor economy of covenant relationship.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'I will cut off your arm (<em>zĕrôʿ</em>) and the arm of your father's house, so that there will not be an old man in your house' — <em>zĕrôʿ</em> (H2220, arm/strength/line) means both physical power and genealogical line. The cutting off of <em>zĕrôʿ</em> combines the end of physical power and the end of genealogical continuation. Near fulfillment: the Nob massacre (22:18-19) kills 85 priests. Ultimate fulfillment: Solomon deposes Abiathar (1 Kgs 2:26-27), fulfilling 'I will cut off your arm from the altar.'</p>",
    "32": "<p>Eli's house will see the prosperity that comes to Israel through the faithful priest — the distress of the sanctuary will be witnessed by the deposed priestly house while YHWH's purposes succeed through another line. The judgment is not only on the guilty generation but on the lineage: the covenant privilege given to Aaron's house cannot be inherited by those who corrupt it. The revision of the eternal promise in v30 ('I promised... but now: far be it from me') demonstrates the conditional nature of priestly privilege — YHWH will fulfill his covenant through a faithful priest, but not through this house.</p>",
    "33": "<p>One survivor is preserved to weep — <em>lĕḵallôt ʾet-ʿênāyw ûlĕdaʾăḇ ʾet-napšô</em> (to wear out his eyes and to grieve his soul). The partial preservation is more bitter than total elimination: the survivor witnesses the complete fulfillment of the oracle without being able to prevent any of it. Fulfilled in Abiathar (1 Kgs 2:26-27), who is exiled to Anathoth and lives to see the Zadokite priesthood replace his line in Solomon's temple. The survivor who witnesses the judgment is the living sign of the oracle's complete fulfillment.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'Both of them shall die on the same day' — the simultaneous death of Hophni and Phinehas as a covenant sign (<em>ʾôt</em>, H226). <em>ʾôt</em> is the same word for the circumcision sign (Gen 17:11) and the Exodus signs — a divine marker that the event is a judgment-act, not historical accident. The precise prediction (same day) makes the fulfillment unambiguous: when both sons die on the same day in 4:11, the entire oracle's reliability is confirmed. The sign-character of their simultaneous death establishes Samuel's prophetic authority — YHWH speaks through him what YHWH then fulfills exactly.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'I will raise up for myself a faithful priest who shall do according to what is in my heart and in my mind' (<em>kōhēn neʾĕmān kăʾăšer bilĕḇāḇî ûḇĕnapšî yāʿăśeh</em>). <em>neʾĕmān</em> (H539, faithful/trustworthy — from <em>ʾāman</em>, the root of 'amen') characterizes the promised priest. The criterion of faithfulness — acting 'according to what is in my heart and in my mind' rather than what serves personal interest — is the inversion of Hophni and Phinehas who acted according to their own appetites. The near fulfillment is Zadok; the ultimate fulfillment is Christ as great high priest who acts entirely according to the Father's will (Heb 5:7-10: he learned obedience through what he suffered and was appointed high priest forever).</p>",
    "36": "<p>The survivors of Eli's house will come to bow before the faithful priest for a piece of silver or a morsel of bread — the descendants of the priests who stole sacrificial portions will beg for scraps. The inversion is precise: they took more than their portion by force (v16); they will receive far less than their portion by begging. The oracle closes the covenant-lawsuit with the pattern of complete reversal: what was taken out of place will be needed in diminishment. The faithful priest who receives the transferred privilege must do 'what is in YHWH's heart and mind' — the only basis on which covenant office can be legitimately held.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>'The word of YHWH was rare (<em>yāqār</em>, H3368) in those days; there was no frequent vision' (<em>ʾên ḥāzôn niphrāṣ</em>). <em>yāqār</em> means precious/rare/scarce — used for precious stones (Prov 3:15; Ps 72:14) and rare events. The scarcity of YHWH's word creates a condition of preciousness-through-absence: rare speech, when it comes, carries extraordinary weight. <em>ḥāzôn</em> (H2377, vision/prophetic revelation) — the technical term for the vision-form of revelation (Isa 1:1; Ezek 1:1). The paired rarity of divine word and prophetic vision describes a period of spiritual drought that simultaneously marks the darkness just before YHWH breaks his silence — and through the most unexpected medium.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Eli's failing eyesight — <em>hēḥēllû ḵĕhôt lōʾ yûḵal lirʾôṯ</em> (had grown so dim he could not see) — is both literal and theologically resonant. The priest who cannot physically see parallels his inability to see the sins of his sons (2:22-24) and his misreading of Hannah's prayer (1:12-14). The root <em>kāhāh</em> (H3543, to grow dim/weak) that describes his eyesight is the same root used in 3:13 for his failure to 'restrain' (<em>kāhāh</em>) his sons. His physical dimming and ethical weakness share the same verb root, making the connection explicit. The prophet who 'sees' (receives visions) is coming to replace the priest who cannot see.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The lamp of God (<em>nēr ʾĕlōhîm</em>) had not yet gone out — the perpetually burning lampstand of the tabernacle (Exod 27:20-21; Lev 24:2-4) burning from evening to morning. 'Not yet gone out' situates the scene just before dawn: the end of the night watch when the lamp's oil was nearly exhausted. Samuel lies near the ark of God (<em>ʾăšer šām ʾărôn hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — the presence-locus of YHWH in the sanctuary. Proximity to YHWH's dwelling is the narrative setup for the divine speech: YHWH speaks to the one lying nearest to him. The lamp about to go out + the ark where YHWH dwells = the last moment of the old order, immediately before the new prophetic era begins.</p>",
    "4": "<p>YHWH calls 'Samuel! Samuel!' — the doubled name is the formula of urgent divine address: Abraham, Abraham (Gen 22:11); Moses, Moses (Exod 3:4); Elijah (1 Kgs 19:13); Martha, Martha (Luke 10:41); Saul, Saul (Acts 9:4). The repetition signals a call requiring total attention and complete response — YHWH is summoning a person into a new relationship, not simply conveying information. Samuel's response <em>hinnēnî</em> (H2009, here I am) is the standard formula of covenant availability: Abraham (Gen 22:1), Moses (Exod 3:4), Isaiah (Isa 6:8). The identical response to YHWH and to Eli (vv5-6) shows Samuel has not yet learned to distinguish the source, but his posture of availability is correct.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Samuel runs to Eli thinking he called. Eli's response — 'I did not call; lie down again' (<em>lōʾ qārāʾṯî šûḇ šĕḵāḇ</em>) — is accurate: he genuinely did not call. The pattern of threefold misidentification (vv5-8) before correct identification is the OT's narration of prophetic formation: the call must be recognized before it can be answered rightly. Samuel's assumption that the voice belongs to Eli is natural (who else would call a child in the sanctuary at night?). The narrative's patience with the three errors reflects the understanding that prophetic formation takes time and correction.</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH calls a second time: 'Samuel!' — and Samuel rises and goes to Eli again. The exact repetition of the call and response sequence with no variation is the narrative's way of showing that the misidentification is genuine, not convenient: Samuel is consistently and sincerely mistaking YHWH's voice for Eli's. The learning process requires the mistake to be repeated until the teacher is able to diagnose the pattern. Eli's second 'I did not call' begins to set up the recognition — he is now hearing the pattern from Samuel's reports that something is happening that is not attributable to him.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Now Samuel did not yet know YHWH' (<em>wĕšĕmûʾēl ṭerem yāḏaʿ ʾet-YHWH</em>) — the same verb <em>yāḏaʿ</em> as 2:12 ('Eli's sons did not know YHWH') but with opposite theological valence. Eli's sons did not know YHWH because of corruption; Samuel does not know him because 'the word of YHWH had not yet been revealed to him' (<em>ṭerem yiggāleh ʾēlāyw dĕḇar-YHWH</em>) — YHWH has not yet initiated the relationship from his side. The not-knowing is circumstantial and about to be remedied by divine revelation. The contrast between the two uses of <em>lōʾ yāḏaʿ</em> within a few verses is the narrator's precise theological characterization: same surface, opposite reality.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH calls a third time. Eli understands (<em>wayyāḇen</em>, H995 — to discern/perceive; the root of wisdom-discernment, <em>bînāh</em>) that YHWH is calling the boy. This is Eli's last moment of genuine spiritual service: he correctly perceives what is happening and gives Samuel the proper response-formula. The priest who cannot see (v2) and who failed to act against his corrupt sons can still discern a genuine divine call when the pattern makes it undeniable. His instruction is theologically correct: &#8216;Say, &#8220;Speak, YHWH, for your servant hears&#8221;&#8217; — he teaches Samuel how to respond to YHWH even though the oracle to follow will pronounce Eli's doom.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The formula Eli gives: <em>dabbēr YHWH kî šōmēaʿ ʿaḇdeḵā</em> (Speak, YHWH, for your servant hears). <em>šāmaʿ</em> (H8085, to hear/obey) is the covenant verb — Deut 6:4 (<em>šĕmaʿ yiśrāʾēl</em>) establishes hearing-that-obeys as the fundamental covenant stance. 'Your servant hears' means 'your servant is in the posture of responsive obedience' — not passive reception but active readiness to respond. The formula models the prophetic stance toward divine speech: total availability, no filtering, responsive action. Samuel will spend his life as a prophet practicing this formula's content.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH comes and stands (<em>wayyāḇōʾ YHWH wayyiṯyaṣṣēḇ</em>) — theophanic presence language: YHWH does not merely send a voice but takes up a standing position, indicating a personal appearance (cf. Gen 18:2; Exod 34:5; Num 22:22). The doubled name formula ('Samuel! Samuel!') repeats the urgency of the initial call. Samuel's response — <em>dabbēr kî šōmēaʿ ʿaḇdeḵā</em> — follows Eli's instruction exactly but omits the divine name: YHWH is present and speaking; the name is not needed for identification. Samuel has learned to address the voice directly.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Behold, I am about to do something in Israel at which the two ears of everyone who hears it will tingle' (<em>ṣilênāh ʾoznê kol-šōmĕʿô</em>). <em>ṣālan</em> (H6750, to tingle/ring) applied to ears describes news so shocking it creates a physical sensation — used only here, 2 Kgs 21:12 (judgment on Manasseh), and Jer 19:3 (judgment on Jerusalem). The formula marks this as one of the most severe judgment pronouncements in the OT. The ear-tingling is the somatic marker of devastating news — the same kind of news that Paul reserves for the severest covenant warnings (Gal 1:8: 'even if we or an angel from heaven should preach to you a gospel contrary to the one we preached to you, let him be accursed').</p>",
    "12": "<p>'I will fulfill against Eli all that I have spoken concerning his house, from beginning to end' (<em>mēhāḵēl wĕʿaḏ-kallōh</em>). The phrase uses <em>ḵālal</em> (begin) and <em>kālāh</em> (complete/finish): from-beginning-to-end, the full oracle will be fulfilled. This total-fulfillment formula is used for YHWH's covenant commitments (both promises and judgments): what is spoken will be completed without remainder. The word of the man of God (2:27-36) is now confirmed by YHWH's direct speech — double confirmation by oracle and divine voice establishes the certainty and scope of what is coming.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'I have told him that I am about to punish his house forever, for the iniquity that he knew, because his sons were blaspheming God, and he did not restrain them' (<em>wĕlōʾ kihāh bām</em>). <em>kāhāh</em> (H3543, to restrain/rebuke/dim) — the same root as Eli's dimming eyes. He did not <em>kihah</em> his sons — he did not rebuke with the force of removal from office. The sons' sin: <em>mĕqallĕlîm</em> (H7043, making light/contemptible/cursing) — they made YHWH's name and service contemptible. The combination of knowing the sin (v22: 'Eli heard everything') and not restraining it makes the guilt shared: Eli's passivity becomes complicity in his sons' contempt.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'The iniquity of Eli's house shall not be atoned for by sacrifice or offering forever' (<em>ʾim-yitkappēr ʿăwōn bêṯ-ʿēlî bĕzēḵaḥ ûḇĕminḥāh ʿaḏ-ʿôlām</em>). This is a severe covenant declaration: the two primary sacrificial forms — <em>zāḵaḥ</em> (animal sacrifice, H2077) and <em>minḥāh</em> (grain offering, H4503) — cannot provide atonement for this sin. The system that Hophni and Phinehas corrupted cannot serve as the mechanism of their house's restoration. Num 15:30-31 establishes that willful, high-handed rebellion (not unintentional sin) is beyond ordinary sacrificial atonement. The Levitical system's limits are here explicitly stated: some sins require a different remedy — which the rest of Scripture will identify as the sin-bearing that only the sinless can perform.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Samuel lay until morning and opened the doors of the sanctuary — his regular morning duty, performed without alteration despite the oracle received. He is afraid to tell the vision (<em>mĕhaggîḏ ʾet-hammārʾeh ʾel-ʿēlî</em>). <em>mārʾeh</em> (H4758, vision/appearance) — the vision received in the night encounter. Samuel's fear is appropriate: the oracle is devastating, and it concerns the man who raised him. The tension between loyalty to Eli and fidelity to YHWH's word is the first test of his prophetic formation. The faithful prophet must report YHWH's word even when it is painful — this test precedes every subsequent oracle Samuel will deliver.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Eli calls 'Samuel, my son!' (<em>šĕmûʾēl bĕnî</em>) — the paternal address invokes the relationship. Samuel responds <em>hinnēnî</em> — the same covenant-availability formula he used with YHWH (v4-8): total responsiveness to both YHWH and to those in authority over him. Eli's request: 'Do not hide it from me' (<em>ʾal-nāʾ tĕḵahēd mimmennî</em>) — <em>kāḥaḏ</em> (H3582, to hide/conceal) inverted: tell me everything, conceal nothing. By explicitly requesting full disclosure, Eli creates the covenant obligation for Samuel to report completely — including the devastating personal dimension of the oracle against Eli's own house.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Eli adds the self-imprecation oath: 'God do so to you and more also if you hide anything from me' (<em>kōh yāʿăśeh-lĕḵā ʾĕlōhîm wĕḵōh yōsîp̄ ʾim-tĕḵaḥēd mimmennî dāḇār</em>). The standard oath formula (Ruth 3:13; 1 Sam 14:44; 2 Sam 3:9) places divine sanctions on Samuel if he withholds anything. Eli has legally bound Samuel to full disclosure. The one who is about to receive the devastating oracle has himself created the obligation for complete reporting — removing any possibility of Samuel softening or omitting elements 'to spare feelings.' Covenant oaths ensure that YHWH's word is transmitted accurately and completely.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel reports everything; Eli's response: 'It is YHWH. Let him do what seems good to him' (<em>YHWH hûʾ haṭṭôḇ bĕʿênāyw yaʿăśeh</em>). This is Eli's finest recorded moment and his last significant speech. Submission to YHWH's covenant judgment — without complaint, without self-defense, without seeking to negotiate — is the correct response to a prophetic verdict. The same formula of submission appears in David (2 Sam 10:12; 15:26) and characterizes the person who understands that YHWH's judgments, even when devastating, are within YHWH's sovereign goodness. Eli receives the oracle against his house with theological integrity even as he receives it without the practical action that might have changed it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'YHWH was with Samuel and let none of his words fall to the ground' (<em>wĕlōʾ-hippîl mikkol-dĕḇārāyw ʾārṣāh</em>). The idiom <em>nāpal ʾārṣāh</em> (to fall to the ground) for prophetic words that fail to fulfill — they 'drop' without reaching their target. YHWH's guarantee that none of Samuel's words fall is the Deuteronomic criterion for a true prophet (Deut 18:21-22: if the word does not come to pass, YHWH did not speak it). Samuel's total reliability as a prophetic channel — established from the first oracle — is the foundation for his national authority. Isa 55:11 applies the same principle to YHWH's word itself: 'it shall not return to me empty.'</p>",
    "20": "<p>'All Israel from Dan to Beersheba' (<em>mîḏān wĕʿaḏ-bĕʾēr šāḇaʿ</em>) — the standard expression for the full national extent: Dan in upper Galilee (northern limit) to Beersheba in the Negev (southern limit), approximately 150 miles. 'Knew that Samuel was established (<em>nĕʾĕmān</em>, H539, confirmed/faithful) as a prophet (<em>nāḇîʾ</em>, H5030) of YHWH.' <em>nāḇîʾ</em> — the standard term for prophet applied to Samuel here for the first time. <em>nĕʾĕmān</em> — from <em>ʾāman</em>, the root of 'amen' — characterizes Samuel's prophetic reliability: his word is confirmed, trustworthy, faithful. The nation's recognition of his prophetic authority is the public side of YHWH's establishment of him as the covenant's human mouthpiece.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'And YHWH continued to appear in Shiloh, for YHWH revealed himself to Samuel at Shiloh by the word of YHWH' (<em>wayyōsep̄ YHWH lĕhērāʾôṯ ḇĕšilōh kî niglāh YHWH ʾel-šĕmûʾēl ḇĕšilôh biḏḇar YHWH</em>). Three revelation verbs in one verse: <em>rāʾāh</em> (appear/be seen, H7200), <em>gālāh</em> (reveal/uncover, H1540), <em>dāḇar</em> (speak/word, H1696). The triple characterization — appearing, revealing, speaking — describes the full range of divine self-disclosure. After v1's rare word and absent vision, YHWH now regularly appears at Shiloh through Samuel. The new prophetic era has begun: the drought of divine speech is over; YHWH's word comes now through his established prophet.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('original', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(c, ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('original', '1samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in ORIGINAL.values())
    print(f'1samuel mkt-original: wrote {total} verses across ch 1-3')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
